{"timestamp":"2026-04-29T20:35:28.950Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"call_iXzJKCDlvcTQ4EcqD4ptxQlL","name":"apply_patch","input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: docs/demo-local-smart-http.sh\n+#!/usr/bin/env bash\n+set -euo pipefail\n+\n+ROOT=\"${GITSYNC_DEMO_ROOT:-$(mktemp -d)}\"\n+SERVER_GO=\"$ROOT/git-http-demo-server.go\"\n+URL_FILE=\"$ROOT/server-url.txt\"\n+LOG_FILE=\"$ROOT/server.log\"\n+\n+cleanup() {\n+  if [[ -n \"${SERVER_PID:-}\" ]]; then\n+    kill \"$SERVER_PID\" >/dev/null 2>&1 || true\n+  fi\n+  if [[ -z \"${GITSYNC_DEMO_ROOT:-}\" ]]; then\n+    rm -rf \"$ROOT\"\n+  else\n+    printf 'kept demo root: %s\\n' \"$ROOT\"\n+  fi\n+}\n+trap cleanup EXIT\n+\n+run() {\n+  printf '\\n$ %s\\n' \"$*\"\n+  \"$@\"\n+}\n+\n+write_server() {\n+  cat >\"$SERVER_GO\" <<'GO'\n+package main\n+\n+import (\n+\t\"fmt\"\n+\t\"log\"\n+\t\"net\"\n+\t\"net/http\"\n+\t\"net/http/cgi\"\n+\t\"os\"\n+\t\"os/exec\"\n+)\n+\n+func main() {\n+\tif len(os.Args) != 3 {\n+\t\tlog.Fatalf(\"usage: %s <repo-root> <url-file>\", os.Args[0])\n+\t}\n+\trepoRoot := os.Args[1]\n+\turlFile := os.Args[2]\n+\n+\tgitPath, err := exec.LookPath(\"git\")\n+\tif err != nil {\n+\t\tlog.Fatal(err)\n+\t}\n+\n+\thandler := &cgi.Handler{\n+\t\tPath: gitPath,\n+\t\tArgs: []string{\"http-backend\"},\n+\t\tEnv: []string{\n+\t\t\t\"GIT_PROJECT_ROOT=\" + repoRoot,\n+\t\t\t\"GIT_HTTP_EXPORT_ALL=1\",\n+\t\t},\n+\t}\n+\n+\tlistener, err := net.Listen(\"tcp\", \"127.0.0.1:0\")\n+\tif err != nil {\n+\t\tlog.Fatal(err)\n+\t}\n+\tbaseURL := \"http://\" + listener.Addr().String()\n+\tif err := os.WriteFile(urlFile, []byte(baseURL), 0o644); err != nil {\n+\t\tlog.Fatal(err)\n+\t}\n+\tfmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \"serving %s at %s\\n\", repoRoot, baseURL)\n+\tlog.Fatal(http.Serve(listener, handler))\n+}\n+GO\n+}\n+\n+setup_repos() {\n+  run git init --bare \"$ROOT/source.git\"\n+  run git init --bare \"$ROOT/target.git\"\n+  run git -C \"$ROOT/target.git\" config http.receivepack true\n+\n+  run git init -b main \"$ROOT/work\"\n+  run git -C \"$ROOT/work\" config user.name \"git-sync demo\"\n+  run git -C \"$ROOT/work\" config user.email \"git-sync@example.com\"\n+  printf 'hello from source\\n' >\"$ROOT/work/README.md\"\n+  run git -C \"$ROOT/work\" add README.md\n+  run git -C \"$ROOT/work\" commit -m \"initial commit\"\n+  run git -C \"$ROOT/work\" remote add origin \"$ROOT/source.git\"\n+  run git -C \"$ROOT/work\" push origin main\n+}\n+\n+wait_for_server() {\n+  for _ in {1..100}; do\n+    if [[ -s \"$URL_FILE\" ]]; then\n+      cat \"$URL_FILE\"\n+      return\n+    fi\n+    sleep 0.1\n+  done\n+  printf 'server did not start; log follows:\\n' >&2\n+  cat \"$LOG_FILE\" >&2 || true\n+  exit 1\n+}\n+\n+write_server\n+setup_repos\n+\n+run mise exec -- go build -o \"$ROOT/git-sync\" ./cmd/git-sync\n+\n+run mise exec -- go run \"$SERVER_GO\" \"$ROOT\" \"$URL_FILE\" >\"$LOG_FILE\" 2>&1 &\n+SERVER_PID=$!\n+BASE_URL=\"$(wait_for_server)\"\n+SOURCE_URL=\"$BASE_URL/source.git\"\n+TARGET_URL=\"$BASE_URL/target.git\"\n+\n+printf '\\nsource: %s\\n' \"$SOURCE_URL\"\n+printf 'target: %s\\n' \"$TARGET_URL\"\n+\n+run \"$ROOT/git-sync\" plan --branch main --json \"$SOURCE_URL\" \"$TARGET_URL\"\n+run \"$ROOT/git-sync\" sync --branch main --json \"$SOURCE_URL\" \"$TARGET_URL\"\n+\n+printf '\\nTarget refs after initial sync:\\n'\n+run git --git-dir=\"$ROOT/target.git\" show-ref\n+\n+printf '\\nAdd a second source commit, then sync incrementally:\\n'\n+printf 'second line\\n' >>\"$ROOT/work/README.md\"\n+run git -C \"$ROOT/work\" add README.md\n+run git -C \"$ROOT/work\" commit -m \"second commit\"\n+run git -C \"$ROOT/work\" push origin main\n+run \"$ROOT/git-sync\" sync --branch main --stats --json \"$SOURCE_URL\" \"$TARGET_URL\"\n+\n+printf '\\nMap source main to target stable:\\n'\n+run \"$ROOT/git-sync\" sync --map main:stable --json \"$SOURCE_URL\" \"$TARGET_URL\"\n+\n+printf '\\nFinal target refs:\\n'\n+run git --git-dir=\"$ROOT/target.git\" show-ref\n+\n+printf '\\nDemo completed successfully.\\n'\n*** Add File: docs/tutorial.md\n+# git-sync Tutorial\n+\n+This project is a Go command-line tool and library for mirroring Git refs from one remote to another without creating a local checkout. The main command is `git-sync`; the benchmark helper is `git-sync-bench`.\n+\n+## 1. Set Up The Toolchain\n+\n+The repo uses `mise` to install Go and the project tools.\n+\n+```bash\n+cd /Users/rizel/Documents/work/gitsync\n+mise install\n+mise exec -- go version\n+```\n+\n+You can run commands through `mise exec -- ...`, or activate mise in your shell and run `go` directly.\n+\n+## 2. Verify The Project\n+\n+Run the default test suite:\n+\n+```bash\n+mise run test\n+```\n+\n+Build the CLI:\n+\n+```bash\n+mise run build\n+```\n+\n+That writes a `git-sync` binary in the repo root. You can also skip the binary and run directly:\n+\n+```bash\n+mise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync --help\n+```\n+\n+Note: the current CLI prints help as an error and exits non-zero for `--help`, but the usage text is still the right reference.\n+\n+## 3. The Main Commands\n+\n+Use `plan` when you want to preview what would happen:\n+\n+```bash\n+mise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync plan --json <source-url> <target-url>\n+```\n+\n+Use `sync` for the normal workflow. It bootstraps an empty target and handles later fast-forward updates:\n+\n+```bash\n+mise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync sync <source-url> <target-url>\n+```\n+\n+Use `replicate` when the source should overwrite the target through relay-only execution. If relay is not possible, it fails instead of falling back to local materialization:\n+\n+```bash\n+mise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync replicate --stats <source-url> <target-url>\n+```\n+\n+Use `probe` to inspect refs and remote capabilities:\n+\n+```bash\n+mise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync probe --tags --json <source-url> <target-url>\n+```\n+\n+Use `fetch` for lower-level source fetch experiments:\n+\n+```bash\n+mise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync fetch --branch main --json <source-url>\n+```\n+\n+Important flag placement: put flags before positional URLs. For example:\n+\n+```bash\n+mise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync sync --branch main --json <source-url> <target-url>\n+```\n+\n+## 4. Local Demo: Smart HTTP Source And Target\n+\n+The main CLI talks Git smart HTTP, so a plain local `file://` URL is not enough for `git-sync sync`. This repo includes a disposable local demo script that creates two bare repos, serves them through `git http-backend`, and runs real CLI commands against them.\n+\n+Run it from the repo root:\n+\n+```bash\n+bash docs/demo-local-smart-http.sh\n+```\n+\n+The script demonstrates:\n+\n+- `plan --branch main --json`\n+- first `sync` into an empty target\n+- an incremental `sync` after a second source commit\n+- `sync --map main:stable` to copy a source branch into a differently named target branch\n+- verification with `git show-ref` inside the bare target\n+\n+By default, the script deletes its temporary files. To keep the demo repos for inspection:\n+\n+```bash\n+GITSYNC_DEMO_ROOT=/tmp/gitsync-demo bash docs/demo-local-smart-http.sh\n+```\n+\n+Then inspect the result:\n+\n+```bash\n+git --git-dir=/tmp/gitsync-demo/source.git show-ref\n+git --git-dir=/tmp/gitsync-demo/target.git show-ref\n+git --git-dir=/tmp/gitsync-demo/target.git log --oneline --all --decorate\n+```\n+\n+## 5. Hosted Remote Example\n+\n+For GitHub or another hosted Git provider, pass HTTPS clone URLs. Tokens can be passed as flags:\n+\n+```bash\n+mise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n+  --source-token \"$GITSYNC_SOURCE_TOKEN\" \\\n+  --target-token \"$GITSYNC_TARGET_TOKEN\" \\\n+  --branch main \\\n+  --json \\\n+  https://github.com/source-org/source-repo.git \\\n+  https://github.com/target-org/target-repo.git\n+```\n+\n+Or set environment variables:\n+\n+```bash\n+export GITSYNC_SOURCE_TOKEN=...\n+export GITSYNC_TARGET_TOKEN=...\n+export GITSYNC_SOURCE_USERNAME=git\n+export GITSYNC_TARGET_USERNAME=git\n+\n+mise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n+  --branch main \\\n+  https://github.com/source-org/source-repo.git \\\n+  https://github.com/target-org/target-repo.git\n+```\n+\n+If your normal Git credential helper knows the remotes, `git-sync` can also use that instead of explicit token flags.\n+\n+## 6. Common Demo Scenarios\n+\n+Mirror only selected branches:\n+\n+```bash\n+mise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n+  --branch main,release \\\n+  <source-url> \\\n+  <target-url>\n+```\n+\n+Mirror tags too:\n+\n+```bash\n+mise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n+  --branch main \\\n+  --tags \\\n+  <source-url> \\\n+  <target-url>\n+```\n+\n+Map a source branch to a different target branch:\n+\n+```bash\n+mise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n+  --map main:stable \\\n+  <source-url> \\\n+  <target-url>\n+```\n+\n+Preview a replicate run:\n+\n+```bash\n+mise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync plan \\\n+  --mode replicate \\\n+  --branch main \\\n+  --json \\\n+  <source-url> \\\n+  <target-url>\n+```\n+\n+Collect transfer statistics and memory measurements:\n+\n+```bash\n+mise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n+  --stats \\\n+  --measure-memory \\\n+  --json \\\n+  <source-url> \\\n+  <target-url>\n+```\n+\n+## 7. Benchmark Demo\n+\n+Build the benchmark helper:\n+\n+```bash\n+mise exec -- go build -o /tmp/git-sync-bench ./cmd/git-sync-bench\n+```\n+\n+Run a small local benchmark against a local source repo path:\n+\n+```bash\n+/tmp/git-sync-bench \\\n+  --scenario bootstrap \\\n+  --source-url /tmp/gitsync-demo/source.git \\\n+  --repeat 3 \\\n+  --branch main \\\n+  --stats \\\n+  --json\n+```\n+\n+For larger real-world tests, use a local mirror as the source rather than repeatedly benchmarking directly against a hosted service.\n+\n+## 8. How To Read The Output\n+\n+In text mode, look for counts like `pushed`, `skipped`, `blocked`, and `deleted`.\n+\n+In JSON mode, the most useful fields are:\n+\n+- `plans`: per-ref planned actions\n+- `pushed`: refs actually updated\n+- `skipped`: refs that were already current\n+- `blocked`: refs that could not update safely\n+- `deleted`: refs pruned from the target\n+- `relay` and `relayMode`: whether the operation used relay, such as `bootstrap` or incremental relay\n+- `stats`: request, byte, want, have, and push-command counters when `--stats` is set\n+- `measurement`: elapsed time and heap data when `--measure-memory` is set\n+\n+If `sync` reports blocked refs, the target has diverged or the requested update is not fast-forwardable. Use `plan --json` to inspect the reason, then decide whether to fix the target, change the ref mapping, or rerun with `--force`.\n+\n+## 9. Where To Look Next\n+\n+- `README.md`: command overview and auth behavior\n+- `docs/architecture.md`: when this tool fits and how relay/materialized paths work\n+- `docs/protocol.md`: smart HTTP protocol details\n+- `docs/testing.md`: default, integration, smoke, and benchmark test commands\n+- `example_test.go`: minimal library API example\n*** End Patch\n"}}
{"timestamp":"2026-04-29T20:35:28.997Z","type":"event_msg","payload":{"type":"patch_apply_end","call_id":"call_iXzJKCDlvcTQ4EcqD4ptxQlL","turn_id":"019ddaf2-801a-7f63-89fe-e14abffdbe5f","stdout":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA docs/demo-local-smart-http.sh\nA docs/tutorial.md\n","stderr":"","success":true,"changes":{"/Users/rizel/Documents/work/gitsync/docs/demo-local-smart-http.sh":{"type":"add","content":"#!/usr/bin/env bash\nset -euo pipefail\n\nROOT=\"${GITSYNC_DEMO_ROOT:-$(mktemp -d)}\"\nSERVER_GO=\"$ROOT/git-http-demo-server.go\"\nURL_FILE=\"$ROOT/server-url.txt\"\nLOG_FILE=\"$ROOT/server.log\"\n\ncleanup() {\n  if [[ -n \"${SERVER_PID:-}\" ]]; then\n    kill \"$SERVER_PID\" >/dev/null 2>&1 || true\n  fi\n  if [[ -z \"${GITSYNC_DEMO_ROOT:-}\" ]]; then\n    rm -rf \"$ROOT\"\n  else\n    printf 'kept demo root: %s\\n' \"$ROOT\"\n  fi\n}\ntrap cleanup EXIT\n\nrun() {\n  printf '\\n$ %s\\n' \"$*\"\n  \"$@\"\n}\n\nwrite_server() {\n  cat >\"$SERVER_GO\" <<'GO'\npackage main\n\nimport (\n\t\"fmt\"\n\t\"log\"\n\t\"net\"\n\t\"net/http\"\n\t\"net/http/cgi\"\n\t\"os\"\n\t\"os/exec\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n\tif len(os.Args) != 3 {\n\t\tlog.Fatalf(\"usage: %s <repo-root> <url-file>\", os.Args[0])\n\t}\n\trepoRoot := os.Args[1]\n\turlFile := os.Args[2]\n\n\tgitPath, err := exec.LookPath(\"git\")\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\tlog.Fatal(err)\n\t}\n\n\thandler := &cgi.Handler{\n\t\tPath: gitPath,\n\t\tArgs: []string{\"http-backend\"},\n\t\tEnv: []string{\n\t\t\t\"GIT_PROJECT_ROOT=\" + repoRoot,\n\t\t\t\"GIT_HTTP_EXPORT_ALL=1\",\n\t\t},\n\t}\n\n\tlistener, err := net.Listen(\"tcp\", \"127.0.0.1:0\")\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\tlog.Fatal(err)\n\t}\n\tbaseURL := \"http://\" + listener.Addr().String()\n\tif err := os.WriteFile(urlFile, []byte(baseURL), 0o644); err != nil {\n\t\tlog.Fatal(err)\n\t}\n\tfmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \"serving %s at %s\\n\", repoRoot, baseURL)\n\tlog.Fatal(http.Serve(listener, handler))\n}\nGO\n}\n\nsetup_repos() {\n  run git init --bare \"$ROOT/source.git\"\n  run git init --bare \"$ROOT/target.git\"\n  run git -C \"$ROOT/target.git\" config http.receivepack true\n\n  run git init -b main \"$ROOT/work\"\n  run git -C \"$ROOT/work\" config user.name \"git-sync demo\"\n  run git -C \"$ROOT/work\" config user.email \"git-sync@example.com\"\n  printf 'hello from source\\n' >\"$ROOT/work/README.md\"\n  run git -C \"$ROOT/work\" add README.md\n  run git -C \"$ROOT/work\" commit -m \"initial commit\"\n  run git -C \"$ROOT/work\" remote add origin \"$ROOT/source.git\"\n  run git -C \"$ROOT/work\" push origin main\n}\n\nwait_for_server() {\n  for _ in {1..100}; do\n    if [[ -s \"$URL_FILE\" ]]; then\n      cat \"$URL_FILE\"\n      return\n    fi\n    sleep 0.1\n  done\n  printf 'server did not start; log follows:\\n' >&2\n  cat \"$LOG_FILE\" >&2 || true\n  exit 1\n}\n\nwrite_server\nsetup_repos\n\nrun mise exec -- go build -o \"$ROOT/git-sync\" ./cmd/git-sync\n\nrun mise exec -- go run \"$SERVER_GO\" \"$ROOT\" \"$URL_FILE\" >\"$LOG_FILE\" 2>&1 &\nSERVER_PID=$!\nBASE_URL=\"$(wait_for_server)\"\nSOURCE_URL=\"$BASE_URL/source.git\"\nTARGET_URL=\"$BASE_URL/target.git\"\n\nprintf '\\nsource: %s\\n' \"$SOURCE_URL\"\nprintf 'target: %s\\n' \"$TARGET_URL\"\n\nrun \"$ROOT/git-sync\" plan --branch main --json \"$SOURCE_URL\" \"$TARGET_URL\"\nrun \"$ROOT/git-sync\" sync --branch main --json \"$SOURCE_URL\" \"$TARGET_URL\"\n\nprintf '\\nTarget refs after initial sync:\\n'\nrun git --git-dir=\"$ROOT/target.git\" show-ref\n\nprintf '\\nAdd a second source commit, then sync incrementally:\\n'\nprintf 'second line\\n' >>\"$ROOT/work/README.md\"\nrun git -C \"$ROOT/work\" add README.md\nrun git -C \"$ROOT/work\" commit -m \"second commit\"\nrun git -C \"$ROOT/work\" push origin main\nrun \"$ROOT/git-sync\" sync --branch main --stats --json \"$SOURCE_URL\" \"$TARGET_URL\"\n\nprintf '\\nMap source main to target stable:\\n'\nrun \"$ROOT/git-sync\" sync --map main:stable --json \"$SOURCE_URL\" \"$TARGET_URL\"\n\nprintf '\\nFinal target refs:\\n'\nrun git --git-dir=\"$ROOT/target.git\" show-ref\n\nprintf '\\nDemo completed successfully.\\n'\n"},"/Users/rizel/Documents/work/gitsync/docs/tutorial.md":{"type":"add","content":"# git-sync Tutorial\n\nThis project is a Go command-line tool and library for mirroring Git refs from one remote to another without creating a local checkout. The main command is `git-sync`; the benchmark helper is `git-sync-bench`.\n\n## 1. Set Up The Toolchain\n\nThe repo uses `mise` to install Go and the project tools.\n\n```bash\ncd /Users/rizel/Documents/work/gitsync\nmise install\nmise exec -- go version\n```\n\nYou can run commands through `mise exec -- ...`, or activate mise in your shell and run `go` directly.\n\n## 2. Verify The Project\n\nRun the default test suite:\n\n```bash\nmise run test\n```\n\nBuild the CLI:\n\n```bash\nmise run build\n```\n\nThat writes a `git-sync` binary in the repo root. You can also skip the binary and run directly:\n\n```bash\nmise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync --help\n```\n\nNote: the current CLI prints help as an error and exits non-zero for `--help`, but the usage text is still the right reference.\n\n## 3. The Main Commands\n\nUse `plan` when you want to preview what would happen:\n\n```bash\nmise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync plan --json <source-url> <target-url>\n```\n\nUse `sync` for the normal workflow. It bootstraps an empty target and handles later fast-forward updates:\n\n```bash\nmise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync sync <source-url> <target-url>\n```\n\nUse `replicate` when the source should overwrite the target through relay-only execution. If relay is not possible, it fails instead of falling back to local materialization:\n\n```bash\nmise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync replicate --stats <source-url> <target-url>\n```\n\nUse `probe` to inspect refs and remote capabilities:\n\n```bash\nmise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync probe --tags --json <source-url> <target-url>\n```\n\nUse `fetch` for lower-level source fetch experiments:\n\n```bash\nmise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync fetch --branch main --json <source-url>\n```\n\nImportant flag placement: put flags before positional URLs. For example:\n\n```bash\nmise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync sync --branch main --json <source-url> <target-url>\n```\n\n## 4. Local Demo: Smart HTTP Source And Target\n\nThe main CLI talks Git smart HTTP, so a plain local `file://` URL is not enough for `git-sync sync`. This repo includes a disposable local demo script that creates two bare repos, serves them through `git http-backend`, and runs real CLI commands against them.\n\nRun it from the repo root:\n\n```bash\nbash docs/demo-local-smart-http.sh\n```\n\nThe script demonstrates:\n\n- `plan --branch main --json`\n- first `sync` into an empty target\n- an incremental `sync` after a second source commit\n- `sync --map main:stable` to copy a source branch into a differently named target branch\n- verification with `git show-ref` inside the bare target\n\nBy default, the script deletes its temporary files. To keep the demo repos for inspection:\n\n```bash\nGITSYNC_DEMO_ROOT=/tmp/gitsync-demo bash docs/demo-local-smart-http.sh\n```\n\nThen inspect the result:\n\n```bash\ngit --git-dir=/tmp/gitsync-demo/source.git show-ref\ngit --git-dir=/tmp/gitsync-demo/target.git show-ref\ngit --git-dir=/tmp/gitsync-demo/target.git log --oneline --all --decorate\n```\n\n## 5. Hosted Remote Example\n\nFor GitHub or another hosted Git provider, pass HTTPS clone URLs. Tokens can be passed as flags:\n\n```bash\nmise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n  --source-token \"$GITSYNC_SOURCE_TOKEN\" \\\n  --target-token \"$GITSYNC_TARGET_TOKEN\" \\\n  --branch main \\\n  --json \\\n  https://github.com/source-org/source-repo.git \\\n  https://github.com/target-org/target-repo.git\n```\n\nOr set environment variables:\n\n```bash\nexport GITSYNC_SOURCE_TOKEN=...\nexport GITSYNC_TARGET_TOKEN=...\nexport GITSYNC_SOURCE_USERNAME=git\nexport GITSYNC_TARGET_USERNAME=git\n\nmise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n  --branch main \\\n  https://github.com/source-org/source-repo.git \\\n  https://github.com/target-org/target-repo.git\n```\n\nIf your normal Git credential helper knows the remotes, `git-sync` can also use that instead of explicit token flags.\n\n## 6. Common Demo Scenarios\n\nMirror only selected branches:\n\n```bash\nmise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n  --branch main,release \\\n  <source-url> \\\n  <target-url>\n```\n\nMirror tags too:\n\n```bash\nmise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n  --branch main \\\n  --tags \\\n  <source-url> \\\n  <target-url>\n```\n\nMap a source branch to a different target branch:\n\n```bash\nmise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n  --map main:stable \\\n  <source-url> \\\n  <target-url>\n```\n\nPreview a replicate run:\n\n```bash\nmise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync plan \\\n  --mode replicate \\\n  --branch main \\\n  --json \\\n  <source-url> \\\n  <target-url>\n```\n\nCollect transfer statistics and memory measurements:\n\n```bash\nmise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n  --stats \\\n  --measure-memory \\\n  --json \\\n  <source-url> \\\n  <target-url>\n```\n\n## 7. Benchmark Demo\n\nBuild the benchmark helper:\n\n```bash\nmise exec -- go build -o /tmp/git-sync-bench ./cmd/git-sync-bench\n```\n\nRun a small local benchmark against a local source repo path:\n\n```bash\n/tmp/git-sync-bench \\\n  --scenario bootstrap \\\n  --source-url /tmp/gitsync-demo/source.git \\\n  --repeat 3 \\\n  --branch main \\\n  --stats \\\n  --json\n```\n\nFor larger real-world tests, use a local mirror as the source rather than repeatedly benchmarking directly against a hosted service.\n\n## 8. How To Read The Output\n\nIn text mode, look for counts like `pushed`, `skipped`, `blocked`, and `deleted`.\n\nIn JSON mode, the most useful fields are:\n\n- `plans`: per-ref planned actions\n- `pushed`: refs actually updated\n- `skipped`: refs that were already current\n- `blocked`: refs that could not update safely\n- `deleted`: refs pruned from the target\n- `relay` and `relayMode`: whether the operation used relay, such as `bootstrap` or incremental relay\n- `stats`: request, byte, want, have, and push-command counters when `--stats` is set\n- `measurement`: elapsed time and heap data when `--measure-memory` is set\n\nIf `sync` reports blocked refs, the target has diverged or the requested update is not fast-forwardable. Use `plan --json` to inspect the reason, then decide whether to fix the target, change the ref mapping, or rerun with `--force`.\n\n## 9. Where To Look Next\n\n- `README.md`: command overview and auth behavior\n- `docs/architecture.md`: when this tool fits and how relay/materialized paths work\n- `docs/protocol.md`: smart HTTP protocol details\n- `docs/testing.md`: default, integration, smoke, and benchmark test commands\n- `example_test.go`: minimal library API example\n"}},"status":"completed"}}
