{"timestamp":"2026-04-29T21:46:43.639Z","type":"event_msg","payload":{"type":"agent_message","message":"Your URLs are just the HTTPS clone URLs for the GitHub repos:\n\n```bash\nhttps://github.com/<source-owner>/<source-repo>.git\nhttps://github.com/<target-owner>/<target-repo>.git\n```\n\nExample shape:\n\n```bash\nSOURCE_URL=\"https://github.com/entire-dev/some-existing-repo.git\"\nTARGET_URL=\"https://github.com/entire-dev/git-sync-demo-target.git\"\n```\n\nFor a safe demo, create a brand new empty target repo on GitHub, like:\n\n```text\ngit-sync-demo-target\n```\n\nThen run:\n\n```bash\nexport GITSYNC_SOURCE_TOKEN=...\nexport GITSYNC_TARGET_TOKEN=...\n\nmise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync plan \\\n  --branch main \\\n  --json \\\n  \"$SOURCE_URL\" \\\n  \"$TARGET_URL\"\n```\n\nThen the actual sync:\n\n```bash\nmise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n  --branch main \\\n  --json \\\n  \"$SOURCE_URL\" \\\n  \"$TARGET_URL\"\n```\n\nIf the source repo is public, you may not need `GITSYNC_SOURCE_TOKEN`, but you almost certainly need `GITSYNC_TARGET_TOKEN` because pushing to the target requires write access.\n\nFor screenshots, I’d use:\n\n```bash\nmise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync plan \\\n  --branch main \\\n  --json \\\n  https://github.com/YOUR_ORG/YOUR_SOURCE.git \\\n  https://github.com/YOUR_ORG/git-sync-demo-target.git\n```\n\nJust don’t point the target at any repo you care about for the demo. Make it empty and disposable.","phase":"final_answer","memory_citation":null}}
{"timestamp":"2026-04-29T21:46:43.639Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"output_text","text":"Your URLs are just the HTTPS clone URLs for the GitHub repos:\n\n```bash\nhttps://github.com/<source-owner>/<source-repo>.git\nhttps://github.com/<target-owner>/<target-repo>.git\n```\n\nExample shape:\n\n```bash\nSOURCE_URL=\"https://github.com/entire-dev/some-existing-repo.git\"\nTARGET_URL=\"https://github.com/entire-dev/git-sync-demo-target.git\"\n```\n\nFor a safe demo, create a brand new empty target repo on GitHub, like:\n\n```text\ngit-sync-demo-target\n```\n\nThen run:\n\n```bash\nexport GITSYNC_SOURCE_TOKEN=...\nexport GITSYNC_TARGET_TOKEN=...\n\nmise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync plan \\\n  --branch main \\\n  --json \\\n  \"$SOURCE_URL\" \\\n  \"$TARGET_URL\"\n```\n\nThen the actual sync:\n\n```bash\nmise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n  --branch main \\\n  --json \\\n  \"$SOURCE_URL\" \\\n  \"$TARGET_URL\"\n```\n\nIf the source repo is public, you may not need `GITSYNC_SOURCE_TOKEN`, but you almost certainly need `GITSYNC_TARGET_TOKEN` because pushing to the target requires write access.\n\nFor screenshots, I’d use:\n\n```bash\nmise exec -- go run ./cmd/git-sync plan \\\n  --branch main \\\n  --json \\\n  https://github.com/YOUR_ORG/YOUR_SOURCE.git \\\n  https://github.com/YOUR_ORG/git-sync-demo-target.git\n```\n\nJust don’t point the target at any repo you care about for the demo. Make it empty and disposable."}],"phase":"final_answer"}}
